### Description

Hey! 

First of all: congrats for the milestone 👏🏿👏🏿👏🏿! I was already taking advantage of signals+ngModel, but the new implementation is at a completely different level. 

As everybody, I started playing with what's available and found an unexcepted behaviour compared to ngModel. Here is a snippet showing what I mean: 
```ts
@Component({
  imports: [Control, FormsModule],
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `
    <h1>Signal forms</h1>

    <label for="first">First:</label>
    <input 
      id="first"
      (input)="firstChange($event.target.value)"
      [control]="form.first" />

    <label for="model">Model:</label>
    <input 
      id="model" 
      (input)="modelChange($event.target.value)"
      [(ngModel)]="model"/>
  `,
})
export class App {
  protected readonly source = signal({ first: '', last: '' });
  protected readonly form = form(this.source);

  protected readonly model = signal('');

  firstChange(value: string) {
    console.log(`
      event: ${value}, 
      first: ${this.form.first().value()}, 
      source: ${JSON.stringify(this.source())}`);
  }

  modelChange(value: string) {
    console.log(`
      event: ${value}, 
      model: ${this.model()}`);
  }
}
```
https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-rdvuqbrw

If you type something in first / model, the behaviours of first / model signals differ: in the input event handlers, first has the old value while model the new one. 

I haven't found any reasonable explanation for this difference (unless I'm missing something very obvious): so I'm inclined to think it's an unwanted difference that could be flagged as a bug. 

I'm perfectly aware this is a very early implementation. So feel free to close the ticket. 

Cheers!

